The doctors wanted a 2013 Collective Bargaining Agreement (CBA) implemented, saying negotiations took two years. 
The agreement gave doctors a 150 to 180 per cent basic pay rise. They also wanted a review of their working conditions, job structures and criteria for promotions. 
They had told the government to address understaffing in hospitals before going back to work.
The unionists braved a 30-day jail term for what the Employment Court said was contempt, after a judge declared the strike illegal in December 2016.





Mr Odinga was with the doctors in court and at Uhuru Park.
He promised to stand with them and vowed to take the CBA fight where it belonged – at the doorsteps of President Uhuru Kenyatta, whom he labelled “incompetent and heartless”.
“This is the time the President should speak out. Many Kenyans have died in hospital and at home while the President is busy championing voter registration,” Mr Odinga told the crowd.
“The government appended its signature on the CBA. You cannot sign an agreement with a party and then arrest the same party. Shame on you!” he said. 
Fast forward to December 7, 2020, when doctors threatened to go on strike, complaining about the same things.
Abandoned his stand



