Mr Odinga abandoned his stand, even “advising” health care workers to respect the oath they took.
“All I want to do is appeal to our doctors to be understanding. We are in a crisis. People are dying.
It is not only doctors who are dying,” Mr Odinga said in Kisumu on Monday.
“This is not the time to hold the government to ransom. Doctors themselves took an oath to protect lives. How can you justify a strike when people are dying?”
Mr Odinga’s utterances have portrayed him as a government apologist, apparently softened by the March 2018 handshake with President Kenyatta.
Even more interesting, the handshake has transformed Deputy President William Ruto to an opposition leader in his own government.
“Health care workers will be properly paid. No woman will pay for maternity care and no Kenyan will travel abroad for treatment. Strikes ended with the government of (Mwai) Kibaki and the man of riddles. The workers are the backbone of the nation,” Dr Ruto said in February 2013, when Jubilee launched its manifesto.
The speech has become a major point of reference when mocking Dr Ruto in his newfound opposition role.
When the 100-day strike had just started in December 2016, he tweeted: “We urge doctors to be humane, go back to work and continue negotiations with the Salaries and Remuneration Commission. A solution will be found.”



