He has now “seen the light”, shouting from rooftops about the government’s misplaced priorities and accusing Mr Odinga of being insensitive to doctors for making the same plea he made in 2016.
“It is reckless and irresponsible for anybody to say we should wait for political processes to find the money to address the pandemic. That is putting the cart before the horse,” Dr Ruto said in Kericho, capitalising on the crisis to attack the Building Bridges Initiative (BBI) he halfheartedly supports.
Doublespeak boat
Yet Mr Odinga and Dr Ruto are not the only ones in the doublespeak boat.
Mr Kenyatta pledged to fix the health sector in the manifesto he launched in 2017.
“We will build a healthy nation and a productive workforce because Kenyans deserve to know they can be treated when at their most vulnerable and because the economic status of a country is closely associated with the health of its people,” the President said. 
“We seek to reduce the cost of health care, which has driven families into financial ruin. We will ensure that every citizen has access to the best possible healthcare at the most affordable cost.”
The words sound hollow today, with operations at most public hospitals disrupted by strikes.Patients are either being moved to private hospitals or home.



