When the 100-day strike ended in 2017, the President admonished doctors.
“We will pay you, but we know you will not return the lives lost during the strike,” he said. He has maintained a loud silence as doctors complain of dying at work and being exposed to a deadly virus.
At Afya House, the building that Health Cabinet Secretary Mutahi Kagwe admits “has its fair share of cartels”, the minister and his juniors cannot put their house in order.
They have a schedule to release Sh5.9 billion protective equipment at the government drugs agency. 
The protective gear have been lying idle at the warehouse as doctors catch the virus in hospital while tending to patients.
While Mr Kagwe told Senators on November 11 that he had written to Kemsa to release the PPE and masks, Kemsa CEO Edward Njoroge told the House on Monday that the agency never received such instructions. 



